WEBVTT

00:00:01.200 --> 00:00:03.520
<v Teacher>Comenzar, what do you think that means?

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:05.760
<v Teacher>Comenzar?

00:00:05.760 --> 00:00:06.720
<v Teacher>To commence.

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:08.400
<v Teacher>To commence, or to start.

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:09.600
<v Teacher>To stop.

00:00:09.340 --> 00:00:15.500
<v Teacher>Again, this exists and you can use it and it's probably easier because it sounds like comments, so it's easier to remember.

00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:19.100
<v Teacher>But there's another verb which is more common, which is empezar

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:20.640
<v Teacher>Empezar.

00:00:20.640 --> 00:00:23.920
<v Teacher>This is a Z, so that's gonna sound th in Spain.

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:26.480
<v Teacher>Empezar in most of Spain.

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:27.920
<v Teacher>Empezar.

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:28.880
<v Student>Empezar.

00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:30.240
<v Teacher>Practice with this one for now.

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:31.280
<v Teacher>This is to start.

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:33.280
<v Teacher>How do you say I start?

00:00:34.859 --> 00:00:37.339
<v Teacher>Good that's what it should be, but what might happen?

00:00:37.339 --> 00:00:38.219
<v Teacher>Empiezo.

00:00:38.219 --> 00:00:39.019
<v Teacher>Empiezo.

00:00:39.019 --> 00:00:41.100
<v Teacher>He starts.

00:00:41.180 --> 00:00:42.539
<v Student>Empiece.

00:00:42.539 --> 00:00:45.339
<v Teacher>What must you do before you make that decision?

00:00:45.339 --> 00:00:47.339
<v Teacher>What must you do?

00:00:47.579 --> 00:00:49.739
<v Teacher>You must go back to the two form.

00:00:49.739 --> 00:00:51.660
<v Teacher>It's a very important habit.

00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:53.180
<v Student>It's empesar.

00:00:53.180 --> 00:00:53.820
<v Teacher>Ah.

00:00:54.140 --> 00:00:55.579
<v Teacher>Empeza.

00:00:55.320 --> 00:00:55.960
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:55.960 --> 00:00:58.520
<v Teacher>And then what might be the next step after Empieza?

00:00:58.520 --> 00:00:59.160
<v Teacher>Empieza.

00:00:59.239 --> 00:01:00.040
<v Teacher>Empieza.

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:02.280
<v Teacher>So this is the process we want to take.

00:01:02.280 --> 00:01:07.800
<v Teacher>It's essential for us to get into that habit of going back to the two form and then we know where we are.

00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:09.960
<v Teacher>Otherwise it's guesswork.

00:01:09.700 --> 00:01:10.580
<v Teacher>Empieza.

00:01:10.580 --> 00:01:12.020
<v Teacher>Empieza empieza.

00:01:12.100 --> 00:01:13.940
<v Teacher>They start.

00:01:13.940 --> 00:01:15.060
<v Teacher>Empieza.

00:01:15.060 --> 00:01:16.020
<v Teacher>Empiezan.

00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:16.580
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:18.740
<v Teacher>You informal.

00:01:18.740 --> 00:01:19.780
<v Student>Empiezas.

00:01:19.780 --> 00:01:20.100
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:20.100 --> 00:01:21.860
<v Teacher>When are you starting?

00:01:23.079 --> 00:01:24.680
<v Student>Cuanto empiezas.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.000
<v Teacher>So the E can split to IE.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.920
<v Teacher>That's something we need to know about the present and it's something we need to be on top of.

00:01:32.920 --> 00:01:35.720
<v Teacher>Now it's in the present that this happens because as we know

00:01:35.740 --> 00:01:41.260
<v Teacher>One of the fundamental elements of the present tense is to have that accent on the penultimate syllable.

00:01:41.260 --> 00:01:45.900
<v Teacher>So it's having the accent on the penultimate syllable that makes that E vulnerable to splitting

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:51.160
<v Teacher>The E might split to IE or the O might split to UE.

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:55.000
<v Teacher>We know this already actually because we have puedo

00:01:55.700 --> 00:01:57.700
<v Teacher>And this is a split O.

00:01:57.700 --> 00:02:01.940
<v Teacher>To be able or to can, of course there is no to can in English.

00:02:01.940 --> 00:02:05.540
<v Teacher>To be able, we say, is poder.

00:02:05.240 --> 00:02:08.200
<v Teacher>Here actually you can see closer that connection with power.

00:02:08.200 --> 00:02:11.880
<v Teacher>Before I said that the word is related to the word power in English.

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:13.240
<v Teacher>El poder.

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:14.600
<v Teacher>El is the masculine.

00:02:14.920 --> 00:02:16.840
<v Teacher>We also saw it's the word for he.

00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:18.900
<v Teacher>It's also the word for the for masculine words.

00:02:18.900 --> 00:02:21.380
<v Teacher>El poder is the power.

00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:22.500
<v Teacher>So here it's a noun.

00:02:22.580 --> 00:02:26.340
<v Teacher>It looks like a verb, but if it has the in front of it, we know it's a noun.

00:02:26.340 --> 00:02:28.740
<v Teacher>El poder, the power.

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:31.220
<v Teacher>Poder to be able.

00:02:31.560 --> 00:02:40.360
<v Teacher>When you take off your ending and you change it for present tense and you stress that oh it splits into UE and you get puedo

00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:46.060
<v Teacher>Again, we can see the same phenomenon happening between words in English and Spanish.

00:02:46.060 --> 00:02:51.660
<v Teacher>So for example, we have the word port in English, but we say Puerto Rico

00:02:52.260 --> 00:02:55.780
<v Teacher>Puerto Rico means the rich pot.

00:02:55.780 --> 00:02:58.900
<v Teacher>Rico means rich or nice or tasty or sweet.

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:00.980
<v Teacher>So pot becomes Puerto.

00:03:00.980 --> 00:03:02.660
<v Teacher>We see the always splitting into UE

00:03:03.620 --> 00:03:06.740
<v Teacher>We have the word force in English.

00:03:06.740 --> 00:03:09.220
<v Teacher>In Spanish it is fuerza.

00:03:09.220 --> 00:03:10.900
<v Teacher>We have the word school.

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:13.860
<v Teacher>In Spanish it is escuela.

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:18.640
<v Teacher>We have corp in like corporate which means body.

00:03:18.640 --> 00:03:21.280
<v Teacher>If corp means body in corporate.

00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:23.360
<v Teacher>How do you think it is in Spanish?

00:03:23.840 --> 00:03:24.720
<v Student>Cuerpo.

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:25.840
<v Teacher>Cuerpo.

00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:26.800
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:31.280
<v Teacher>We have innovative, and this nov in innovative means new.

00:03:31.280 --> 00:03:33.840
<v Teacher>When you do something innovative, you do something new.

00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:38.160
<v Teacher>And the word for new in Spanish is nuevo.

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:39.560
<v Teacher>So you saw the ore splitting there.

00:03:39.560 --> 00:03:41.560
<v Teacher>You might have had Pueblo before.

00:03:41.560 --> 00:03:45.400
<v Teacher>Pueblo means a village or a people.

00:03:45.400 --> 00:03:46.760
<v Teacher>Population?

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:49.440
<v Teacher>in Spanish is one of these exceptions.

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:52.720
<v Teacher>It's not poblacion, it's poblacion.

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:55.680
<v Teacher>You can see the connection between pob

00:03:56.140 --> 00:04:02.459
<v Teacher>Lacion, Poblacion, and Pueblo, which means village or people, a people.

00:04:02.459 --> 00:04:06.780
<v Teacher>You can see the O in Pob splitting to UE in Pueblo

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:10.400
<v Teacher>Mortgage, by the way, actually means death pact.

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:19.760
<v Teacher>You have mort, which is the Latin root for death, and gauge, which means pact, and the word for dead in Spanish is have a guess.

00:04:20.299 --> 00:04:22.300
<v Student>Muerto or muerte.

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:27.260
<v Teacher>Well actually here one you have the noun, la muerte is a d-def.

00:04:27.260 --> 00:04:29.660
<v Teacher>So the noun is the word you put the in front of.

00:04:29.660 --> 00:04:32.940
<v Teacher>At school they tell you that it's the the thing

00:04:33.139 --> 00:04:35.540
<v Teacher>the object, but this is not an object.

00:04:35.699 --> 00:04:39.540
<v Teacher>We would think of it, we put though in front of it, it's a noun, la muerte.

00:04:39.540 --> 00:04:46.020
<v Teacher>But then the adjective which is describing is muerto o muerta, o muertos o muertas

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:52.960
<v Teacher>So you can see in those words between English and Spanish this phenomenon of this O splitting into UE when it takes the stress.

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:55.280
<v Teacher>So this is useful for us for present tense.

00:04:55.280 --> 00:04:57.360
<v Teacher>We need to know this for present tense

00:04:57.260 --> 00:05:03.900
<v Teacher>Because if we have a verb like dormir, for example, it has an O in the root, when we stress it it might split.

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:06.380
<v Teacher>What do you think dormir means?

00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:09.220
<v Student>Sting still or dormant?

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:10.260
<v Teacher>Yeah, what does yeah.

00:05:10.260 --> 00:05:11.460
<v Teacher>What does dormant mean?

00:05:11.460 --> 00:05:13.220
<v Teacher>A dormant volcano?

00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:15.620
<v Teacher>It actually means it's a sleeping volcano.

00:05:15.940 --> 00:05:16.980
<v Teacher>Oh dormitory.

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:19.780
<v Teacher>This is a nice collection to make a swear.

00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:21.620
<v Teacher>So dormir means to sleep.

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:23.379
<v Teacher>How do you say I sleep?

00:05:23.699 --> 00:05:24.659
<v Teacher>Duermo.

00:05:24.659 --> 00:05:25.379
<v Teacher>Duermo.

00:05:25.379 --> 00:05:25.780
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:25.780 --> 00:05:30.020
<v Teacher>In Spanish if you want to say I fall asleep, you can say I sleep myself.

00:05:30.020 --> 00:05:31.940
<v Teacher>So how would that sound?

00:05:32.599 --> 00:05:34.120
<v Student>Me duermo.

00:05:34.120 --> 00:05:37.879
<v Teacher>Me duermo, which means I fall asleep rather than duermo, I sleep.

00:05:37.879 --> 00:05:40.120
<v Teacher>So you can say I'm falling asleep, me duermo.

00:05:40.120 --> 00:05:41.000
<v Teacher>It's so boring.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:42.680
<v Teacher>Me duermo.

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:44.120
<v Teacher>He sleeps

00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:45.979
<v Student>Duerme.

00:05:45.979 --> 00:05:46.860
<v Teacher>Duerme.

00:05:46.860 --> 00:05:47.340
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:47.340 --> 00:05:49.259
<v Teacher>They sleep.

00:05:49.259 --> 00:05:50.220
<v Student>Duermen.

00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:51.180
<v Teacher>Duermen.

00:05:51.180 --> 00:05:53.659
<v Teacher>What do you think encontrar means?

00:05:53.659 --> 00:05:55.340
<v Teacher>Encontrar?

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:57.200
<v Student>To encounter.

00:05:57.200 --> 00:05:59.920
<v Teacher>Good, which probably means To meet.

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:00.640
<v Teacher>Oh it does.

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:02.000
<v Teacher>It means that as well.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.720
<v Teacher>But there's a more usual meaning as well.

00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:05.720
<v Student>To find?

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:06.760
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:09.320
<v Teacher>So I'm finding it or I find it.

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:10.600
<v Teacher>How would you say that?

00:06:12.120 --> 00:06:13.480
<v Student>Law ah

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:16.040
<v Student>Is it encuentro?

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:17.080
<v Teacher>Yes, it is.

00:06:17.080 --> 00:06:19.240
<v Student>Lo encuentro.

00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:20.680
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:20.680 --> 00:06:24.280
<v Teacher>Something useful to bear in mind is that different versions of the verb.

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:31.760
<v Teacher>either the two form or some other version might be the noun so you mustn't assume always that it's a verb if you see un encuentro

00:06:32.680 --> 00:06:34.200
<v Teacher>An encounter.

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:35.800
<v Teacher>This is now a noun.

00:06:35.800 --> 00:06:36.920
<v Teacher>An encounter.

00:06:36.920 --> 00:06:39.800
<v Teacher>Whatever we can put a or the in front of is noun.

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:44.520
<v Teacher>So many times some version of the verb will be the noun.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:50.100
<v Teacher>Un encuentro is an encounter, but encuentro I encounter.

00:06:50.260 --> 00:06:53.220
<v Teacher>Demonstrar was to demonstrate, and if we get rid of this de

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:56.420
<v Teacher>We get mostrar, which means to show.

00:06:56.420 --> 00:06:57.540
<v Teacher>Mostrar.

00:06:57.540 --> 00:06:59.700
<v Teacher>So how would you say I show?

00:07:01.140 --> 00:07:02.180
<v Teacher>Mostro.

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:03.620
<v Teacher>It would be mostro.

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:04.420
<v Student>Muestro.

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:05.300
<v Teacher>Muestro.

00:07:05.300 --> 00:07:05.780
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:06.740
<v Teacher>He shows

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:12.180
<v Student>Muestre, wait, muestrar muestra.

00:07:12.180 --> 00:07:13.300
<v Teacher>Good, muestra.

00:07:13.300 --> 00:07:16.020
<v Teacher>We don't need to roll the R here because it's just one R.

00:07:16.020 --> 00:07:16.820
<v Teacher>Muestra.

00:07:16.820 --> 00:07:17.380
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:21.620
<v Teacher>And una muestra actually is a sample.

00:07:21.539 --> 00:07:24.419
<v Teacher>So there is a noun there that shares that version.

00:07:24.419 --> 00:07:29.139
<v Teacher>Muestra, he shows, it shows, she shows, you fool show.

00:07:29.139 --> 00:07:32.580
<v Teacher>But una muestra is a sample.

00:07:32.580 --> 00:07:33.539
<v Teacher>They show

00:07:35.080 --> 00:07:37.400
<v Teacher>Muestran, muestran.

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:38.680
<v Teacher>Good.

